Step 1: Calculate the Debt to Asset Ratio.
• From the balance sheet, Total Liabilities can be deduced as:
 Total Liabilities = Total Liabilities and Owner's Equity – Total Owner's Equity 
  = 19,520,226.07 – 16,143,922.03 
  = 3,376,304.04
• Total Assets at end_date is: 19,520,226.07
• Debt to Asset Ratio = Total Liabilities / Total Assets 
  = 3,376,304.04 / 19,520,226.07 
  ≈ 0.1729 
Rounded, this is approximately 0.17.

Step 2: Calculate the Gross Profit Margin.
• From the income statement:
 Gross Profit = 308,309.79
 Total Revenue = 851,679.79
• Gross Profit Margin = (Gross Profit / Total Revenue) × 100%
  = (308,309.79 / 851,679.79) × 100%
  ≈ 36.196% 
Rounded, this is approximately 36.20%.

Step 3: Calculate the Operating Cash Flow Ratio.
• From the cash flow statement:
 Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities = -4,510,837.08
• From the balance sheet:
 Total Current Liabilities = 3,376,304.04
• Operating Cash Flow Ratio = Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities / Total Current Liabilities 
  = -4,510,837.08 / 3,376,304.04 
  ≈ -1.335
Rounded, this is approximately -1.33.

Thus, the solution is:
{
  "solution": {
    "Debt to Asset Ratio": "0.17",
    "Gross Profit Margin": "36.20%",
    "Operating Cash Flow Ratio": "-1.33"
  }
}
